{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499267"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:57:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:57:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1477"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1477"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.46,0.1,0.24,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1477"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76737"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1477"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1477"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62230"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"774"},{"type":"tags","id":"1131"},{"type":"tags","id":"6351"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6790"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6861"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12404"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76737"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with recurrent left knee pain. He has had crepitations in his knee for years but in the last few months he has experienced pain and his knee \u0027locking\u0027 when trying to stand from sitting. He has a history of playing football for the local club all his life and has sustained several knee injuries in the past. He now mostly coaches but occasionally plays on the old boys day. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The left knee is normal in appearance with some minor swelling. There is no tenderness on palpation. An X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Accessory bone","Bipartite patella","Patella fracture","Loose body","Foreign body"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray shows a large \u003Cstrong\u003Eloose body\u003C/strong\u003E in the suprapatellar pouch. Loose bodies are fragments of cartilage or bone that float freely within the joint space. They can originate from an old fracture, an osteophyte, or osteochondritis dissecans. The patient\u0027s history of recurrent knee injuries and the recent onset of locking symptoms are consistent with this diagnosis. Loose bodies can cause intermittent locking of the joint when they become trapped between the articulating surfaces.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccessory bones\u003C/strong\u003E or accessory ossicles are typically found in the lateral head of the gastrocnemius muscle in the posterolateral capsule of the knee joint. The X-ray indicates something in the suprapatellar pouch which would rule this option out.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBipartite patella\u003C/strong\u003E is a congenital condition caused by failure of the patella to fuse during childhood. It is often an incidental finding and is usually asymptomatic. Bipartite patella typically appears as a well-corticated fragment at the superolateral aspect of the patella, which is not the case in this X-ray. Additionally, the patient\u0027s age and recent onset of symptoms make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatella fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the X-ray indicates an intact patella. Acute patella fractures are typically associated with direct trauma and would present with more severe symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForeign body\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as there is no history of penetrating injury. Foreign bodies in the knee joint are rare and usually associated with a clear history of penetrating trauma or surgery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Loose bodies in the knee can cause locking of the joint.","Loose bodies are often associated with a history of trauma or osteoarthritis."],"references":["Attarian DE, Guilak F. Observations on the growth of loose bodies in joints. Arthroscopy. 2002 Oct;18(8):930-4. doi: 10.1053/jars.2002.36143. PMID: 12368793.","Kay PR, Freemont AJ, Davies DR. The aetiology of multiple loose bodies. Snow storm knee. J Bone Joint Surg Br. 1989 May;71(3):501-4. doi: 10.1302/0301-620X.71B3.2656722. Erratum in: J Bone Joint Surg [Br] 1989 Nov;71(5):890. PMID: 2656722.","Schwab A, Pap T, Krenn V, R\u00fcther W, Lohmann C, Bertrand J. Loose Bodies Found in the Human Intra-Articular Space Showed Characteristics Similar to Endochondral Bone Formation. Cartilage. 2024 Dec;15(4):353-362. doi: 10.1177/19476035231212608. Epub 2023 Dec 1. PMID: 38041252; PMCID: PMC11519999."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62230"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1477"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16717"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16717"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/44acc5ac-6c72-462e-8f16-232d7d33d613.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/44acc5ac-6c72-462e-8f16-232d7d33d613.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":516}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62230","links":{"self":"https